  {
    id: 18, category: 'Soil & Climate', topic: 'Alluvial Soil',
    question: 'Which is the most widespread soil type in India and where is it found?',
    answer: 'Alluvial Soil — covers 43% of land area, found in Indo-Gangetic Plains, river deltas, and coastal plains',
    options: ['Alluvial Soil — covers 43% of land area, found in Indo-Gangetic Plains, river deltas, and coastal plains', 'Black Soil (Regur) — covers 16% of land area, found in Deccan Trap region of Maharashtra and Gujarat', 'Red Soil — covers 18% of land area, found in Deccan Plateau and parts of eastern India', 'Laterite Soil — found in high rainfall tropical regions of Kerala and Karnataka'],
    shortcut: 'Alluvial = 43% of India | Most fertile | Indo-Gangetic plains | New alluvium = Khadar | Old alluvium = Bhangar | Crops: rice, wheat, sugarcane, jute',
    detail: 'Alluvial soil is the most widespread (43% of land). Found in Indo-Gangetic plains, Brahmaputra valley, and coastal areas. New alluvium (Khadar) is deposited by floods — more fertile. Old alluvium (Bhangar) is above flood levels — contains kankar (calcium carbonate nodules). Suitable for rice, wheat, sugarcane, jute, pulses.',
    context: 'SSC CGL 2021-2024', examProb: 'Hot',
    tamilNote: 'வண்டல் மண் = இந்தியாவின் மிகப் பரந்த மண் (43%). கடார் = புதிய வண்டல் | பாங்கர் = பழைய வண்டல். நெல், கோதுமை, கரும்பு பயிரிட ஏற்றது.',
  },
  {
    id: 19, category: 'Soil & Climate', topic: 'Black Soil (Regur)',
    question: 'Which soil is called "Regur" and is ideal for cotton cultivation?',
    answer: 'Black Soil (Regur/Black Cotton Soil) — found in Deccan Trap region: Maharashtra, Gujarat, MP, AP, Karnataka',
    options: ['Black Soil (Regur/Black Cotton Soil) — found in Deccan Trap region: Maharashtra, Gujarat, MP, AP, Karnataka', 'Alluvial Soil (Khadar/Bhangar) — found in Indo-Gangetic Plains, ideal for wheat and rice', 'Red Soil — found in Deccan Plateau and Eastern India, ideal for millets and groundnut', 'Laterite Soil — found in Kerala and Karnataka hills, ideal for tea and coffee'],
    shortcut: 'Black Soil = Regur = Black Cotton Soil | Deccan Trap (lava) | Self-ploughing | High moisture retention | Iron, lime, magnesia rich | Ideal for cotton',
    detail: 'Black soil (Regur) forms from weathering of Deccan Trap lava. Rich in iron, lime, alumina, magnesia but poor in nitrogen, phosphorus. Excellent moisture retention — swells when wet, cracks when dry ("self-ploughing"). Found in Maharashtra, Gujarat, MP, parts of AP, Karnataka, Tamil Nadu. Best for cotton cultivation.',
    context: 'SSC CGL 2022 Tier 1', examProb: 'Confirmed',
    tamilNote: 'கருப்பு மண் = ரேகர் = பருத்தி மண். டெக்கான் பீடபூமி எரிமலை லாவாவிலிருந்து உருவானது. ஈரப்பதத்தை தக்கவைக்கும். பருத்தி சாகுபடிக்கு சிறந்தது.',
  },
  {
    id: 20, category: 'Soil & Climate', topic: 'Laterite Soil',
    question: 'Which soil type is found in regions of heavy rainfall and high temperatures?',
    answer: 'Laterite Soil — formed by leaching in tropical regions; suitable for tea, coffee, rubber, cashew plantations',
    options: ['Laterite Soil — formed by leaching in tropical regions; suitable for tea, coffee, rubber, cashew plantations', 'Desert Soil — formed in arid regions; sandy, saline, low organic content, suitable for drought-resistant crops', 'Mountain Soil — formed in hilly regions; rich in humus, acidic, suitable for apples and temperate fruits', 'Peaty Soil — formed in marshy/swampy areas; high organic content, waterlogged, found in Odisha and Kerala'],
    shortcut: 'Laterite = heavy rain + high temp | Intense leaching | Red color (iron oxide) | Poor in nitrogen/potassium | Plantation crops: tea, coffee, rubber | Found: Kerala, Karnataka, WB hills',
    detail: 'Laterite soil forms in regions of heavy rainfall and high temperature through intense leaching. Rich in iron oxide (red color) and aluminium. Poor in nitrogen, potassium, lime. Found in Kerala, Karnataka, Tamil Nadu hills, Meghalaya, Odisha. Best for plantation crops: tea, coffee, rubber, cashew. Named from Latin "later" = brick.',
    context: 'SSC CGL 2023', examProb: 'High',
    tamilNote: 'லேட்டரைட் மண் = அதிக மழை + வெப்பம் உள்ள பகுதிகளில் காணப்படும். தேயிலை, காப்பி, ரப்பர் சாகுபடிக்கு ஏற்றது. கேரளா, கர்நாடகா.',
  },
  {
    id: 21, category: 'Soil & Climate', topic: 'Red Soil',
    question: 'Why is Red Soil red in color and where is it found?',
    answer: 'Due to high iron content (iron oxide/ferric oxide) — found in Deccan Plateau, Odisha, Chhattisgarh, southern Tamil Nadu',
    options: ['Due to high iron content (iron oxide/ferric oxide) — found in Deccan Plateau, Odisha, Chhattisgarh, southern Tamil Nadu', 'Due to presence of manganese dioxide — found in Central India and parts of West Bengal', 'Due to high humus content (decomposed organic matter) — found in forest regions of Northeast India', 'Due to calcium carbonate (kankar) deposits — found in old alluvium (Bhangar) of Indo-Gangetic plains'],
    shortcut: 'Red Soil = Iron oxide (Fe2O3) | Crystalline igneous rocks | Low rainfall areas | Deccan Plateau | Crops: millets, pulses, groundnuts | Less fertile than alluvial',
    detail: 'Red soil develops on crystalline igneous rocks in low rainfall areas. Red color due to diffusion of iron in crystalline and metamorphic rocks. Found in Eastern and Southern Deccan Plateau — Tamil Nadu, Karnataka, Andhra Pradesh, Odisha, Chhattisgarh, Jharkhand. Crops: millets, pulses, groundnuts. Can be made productive with irrigation and fertilizers.',
    context: 'SSC CGL 2024', examProb: 'High',
    tamilNote: 'சிவப்பு மண் = இரும்பு ஆக்ஸைடு (Fe2O3) காரணமாக சிவப்பு நிறம். குறைந்த மழை பகுதிகளில் காணப்படும். சிறுதானியங்கள், பருப்பு, நிலக்கடலை.',
  },
  {
    id: 22, category: 'Soil & Climate', topic: 'Indian Monsoon System',
    question: 'What causes the Indian Monsoon and when does the SW monsoon arrive?',
    answer: 'Differential heating of land and sea + ITCZ shift — SW monsoon arrives in Kerala by June 1 (±7 days)',
    options: ['Differential heating of land and sea + ITCZ shift — SW monsoon arrives in Kerala by June 1 (±7 days)', 'Jet stream reversal — SW monsoon arrives in Kerala by March 1 (±7 days)', 'El Niño-Southern Oscillation (ENSO) — SW monsoon arrives in Kerala by April 1 (±7 days)', 'Low-pressure system over the Bay of Bengal — SW monsoon arrives in Kerala by August 1 (±7 days)'],
    shortcut: 'SW Monsoon = Jun 1 (Kerala) → mid-Jun (rest of India) | Two branches: Arabian Sea + Bay of Bengal | 70-80% rainfall | NE Monsoon = Oct-Dec (TN, AP) | Mawsynram = highest rainfall',
    detail: 'Indian monsoon is driven by differential heating of land/sea and northward shift of ITCZ. SW monsoon (June-Sep) brings 70-80% of annual rainfall. Two branches: Arabian Sea branch (hits Western Ghats first) and Bay of Bengal branch. Arrives Kerala June 1 (±7 days), covers all India by mid-July. NE Monsoon (Oct-Dec) brings rain to Tamil Nadu and AP coast. Mawsynram (Meghalaya) receives the highest rainfall.',
    context: 'SSC CGL 2022-2024', examProb: 'Hot',
    tamilNote: 'தென்மேற்குப் பருவமழை = ஜூன் 1 (கேரளா) | 70-80% மழையைத் தருகிறது. வடகிழக்குப் பருவமழை = அக்-டிச (தமிழ்நாடு, ஆந்திரா). மாசின்ராம் = அதிக மழை.',
  },
  {
    id: 23, category: 'Soil & Climate', topic: 'Climate Zones of India',
    question: 'According to Koppen classification, what are the major climate zones of India?',
    answer: 'Tropical Wet (Am), Tropical Wet-Dry (Aw), Semi-Arid (BSh), Arid (BWh), Humid Subtropical (Cwa), Alpine (ET/EF)',
    options: ['Tropical Wet (Am), Tropical Wet-Dry (Aw), Semi-Arid (BSh), Arid (BWh), Humid Subtropical (Cwa), Alpine (ET/EF)', 'Polar (EF), Tundra (ET), Subarctic (Dfc), Continental (Dfb), Mediterranean (Csa), Tropical (Af)', 'Equatorial (Af), Monsoon (Am), Savanna (Aw), Desert (BWh), Steppe (BSk), Tundra (ET)', 'Tropical Rainforest, Deciduous Forest, Grassland, Desert, Alpine Tundra, Cold Desert'],
    shortcut: 'Western Ghats/NE = Tropical Wet | Most of Peninsular = Tropical Wet-Dry | Rajasthan = Arid | Indo-Gangetic = Humid Subtropical | Himalayas = Alpine/Tundra',
    detail: 'India has diverse climate zones. Tropical Wet: Western coast, NE India. Tropical Wet & Dry (Savanna): Most of Peninsular India. Semi-Arid: Parts of Rajasthan, Gujarat, Deccan. Arid: Western Rajasthan (Thar Desert). Humid Subtropical: Indo-Gangetic Plain. Mountain: Himalayas. India is between Tropic of Cancer and Equator. Tropic of Cancer (23.5 N) passes through 8 Indian states.',
    context: 'SSC CGL Recurring', examProb: 'High',
    tamilNote: 'இந்தியாவின் காலநிலை மண்டலங்கள்: வெப்ப ஈரம் (மேற்கு கடற்கரை), வெப்ப ஈர-உலர் (தீபகற்பம்), பாலைவனம் (ராஜஸ்தான்), ஈர மிதவெப்பம் (கங்கை சமவெளி), மலை (இமயம்).',
  },
  {
    id: 24, category: 'Soil & Climate', topic: 'Tropic of Cancer Through India',
    question: 'Through how many Indian states does the Tropic of Cancer pass?',
    answer: '8 states — Gujarat, Rajasthan, Madhya Pradesh, Chhattisgarh, Jharkhand, West Bengal, Tripura, Mizoram',
    options: ['8 states — Gujarat, Rajasthan, Madhya Pradesh, Chhattisgarh, Jharkhand, West Bengal, Tripura, Mizoram', '6 states — Rajasthan, Madhya Pradesh, Jharkhand, West Bengal, Tripura, Mizoram', '7 states — Gujarat, Rajasthan, Madhya Pradesh, Chhattisgarh, West Bengal, Tripura, Mizoram', '9 states — Gujarat, Rajasthan, Madhya Pradesh, Chhattisgarh, Jharkhand, Odisha, West Bengal, Tripura, Mizoram'],
    shortcut: 'Tropic of Cancer = 23.5°N | 8 states: GRiMC-JhWTM | Gujarat→Rajasthan→MP→Chhattisgarh→Jharkhand→WB→Tripura→Mizoram',
    detail: 'The Tropic of Cancer (23.5°N latitude) passes through 8 Indian states from west to east: Gujarat, Rajasthan, Madhya Pradesh, Chhattisgarh, Jharkhand, West Bengal, Tripura, and Mizoram. It roughly divides India into tropical (south) and subtropical (north) zones. This is one of the most frequently asked geography questions in SSC exams.',
    context: 'SSC CGL 2019-2024 Recurring', examProb: 'Hot',
    tamilNote: 'கடகரேகை = 23.5°வட அட்சரேகை | 8 மாநிலங்கள் வழியாகச் செல்கிறது: குஜராத், ராஜஸ்தான், மத்தியப்பிரதேசம், சத்தீஸ்கர், ஜார்கண்ட், மேற்கு வங்கம், திரிபுரா, மிசோரம்.',
