  {
    id: 81, category: 'Dams & Irrigation', topic: 'Indira Gandhi Canal',
    question: 'Which is the longest canal in India?',
    answer: 'Indira Gandhi Canal (Rajasthan Canal) — 649 km, carries Sutlej-Beas water from Harike Barrage to Thar Desert',
    options: ['Indira Gandhi Canal (Rajasthan Canal) — 649 km, carries Sutlej-Beas water from Harike Barrage to Thar Desert', 'Upper Ganga Canal — 565 km, carries Ganga water from Haridwar to Kanpur in Uttar Pradesh', 'Buckingham Canal — 796 km, coastal canal along the Coromandel Coast of Andhra Pradesh and Tamil Nadu', 'Son Canal System — 130 km, carries Son River water for irrigation in Madhya Pradesh and Uttar Pradesh'],
    shortcut: 'Indira Gandhi Canal = 649 km | LONGEST canal in India | Harike Barrage (Punjab) → Thar Desert | Sutlej-Beas water | Greened the desert | Named 1984',
    detail: 'Indira Gandhi Canal (formerly Rajasthan Canal, renamed 1984) is India\'s longest canal at 649 km. It carries water from the Harike Barrage (confluence of Sutlej and Beas rivers in Punjab) to the arid western Rajasthan (Thar Desert). Has transformed desert land into productive agricultural land. One of the most ambitious irrigation projects.',
    context: 'SSC CGL 2022', examProb: 'Confirmed',
    tamilNote: 'இந்திரா காந்தி கால்வாய் = 649 கி.மீ = இந்தியாவின் மிக நீளமான கால்வாய். ஹரிகே அணை → தார் பாலைவனம். சட்லஜ்-பியாஸ் நீர்.',
  },
  {
    id: 82, category: 'World Geography', topic: 'Earthquake Zones',
    question: 'How many seismic zones does India have?',
    answer: '5 seismic zones (Zone I removed, effectively 4 active: Zone II to V) — Zone V is highest risk (NE India, J&K, Himachal)',
    options: ['5 seismic zones (Zone I removed, effectively 4 active: Zone II to V) — Zone V is highest risk (NE India, J&K, Himachal)', '3 seismic zones (Low, Moderate, High risk) — High risk covers entire Himalayan region and NE India', '4 seismic zones (Zone I to IV) — Zone I is safest (Deccan Plateau) and Zone IV is highest risk (NE India)', '6 seismic zones (Zone I to VI) — Zone VI is highest risk and covers the entire Himalayan belt'],
