  {
    id: 120, category: 'World Geography', topic: 'Types of Rocks',
    question: 'What are the three main types of rocks?',
    answer: 'Igneous (from magma/lava), Sedimentary (from deposition), Metamorphic (from heat/pressure transformation)',
    options: ['Igneous (from magma/lava), Sedimentary (from deposition), Metamorphic (from heat/pressure transformation)', 'Volcanic (from lava), Alluvial (from water deposits), Crystalline (from cooling of minerals)', 'Primary rocks (formed first), Secondary rocks (formed from primary), Tertiary rocks (formed from secondary)', 'Intrusive rocks (cooled underground), Extrusive rocks (cooled on surface), Mixed rocks (cooled at boundaries)'],
    shortcut: 'Igneous = Primary rocks (Granite, Basalt, Pumice) | Sedimentary = from deposits (Limestone, Sandstone, Shale) | Metamorphic = heat+pressure (Marble, Slate, Quartzite) | Deccan Trap = Basalt (igneous)',
    detail: 'Igneous rocks: formed from cooling of magma/lava. Intrusive (Granite — cooled slowly underground) and Extrusive (Basalt — cooled quickly on surface). Deccan Trap is basalt. Sedimentary: formed from deposition/cementation (Limestone, Sandstone, Shale — contain fossils). Metamorphic: transformation under heat/pressure (Limestone → Marble, Shale → Slate, Sandstone → Quartzite). Rock cycle connects all three.',
